al, and often state-funded enterprises support various cultural and political projects. The contributors to Anthropology, Film Industries, Modularity take an ethnographic and comparative approach to capturing the diversity and growth of global film industries. They outline how modularity—the specialized filmmaking tasks that collectively produce a film—operates as a key feature in every film industry, independent of local context. Whether they are examining the process of dubbing Hollywood films into Hindi, virtual reality filmmaking in South Africa, or on-location shooting in Yemen, the contributors' anthropological methodology brings into relief the universal practices and the local contingencies and deeper cultural realities of film production.Contributors. Steven C. Caton, Jessica Dickson, Kevin Dwyer, Tejaswini Ganti, Lotte Hoek, Amrita Ibrahim, Sylvia J. Martin, Ramyar D. Rossoukh  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picture industryvCross-cultural studies. 0aMotion picture industryxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCaton, Steven C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaton, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanti, Tejaswini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoek, Lotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbrahim, Amrita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRossoukh, Ramyar D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRossouk